display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> be a local ring, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A\to \mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex> a local homomorphism such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex> is isomorphic to the localisation of an algebra of finite type over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
    Suppose that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>unramified</fr:em> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
    Then we can find an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-algebra <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> that is integral over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, a maximal ideal <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {n}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, a generator <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, and a monic polynomial <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F\in  A[t]]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {n}\not \ni  F'(u)]]></fr:tex> and such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex> is isomorphic (as an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-algebra) to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B_\mathfrak {n}]]></fr:tex>.
    If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex> is étale over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, then we can take <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B=A[t]/FA[t]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>